I don't really go to Adams Morgan much these days but this place (and Federalist Pig...) may convince me to make the trip over more often.  I've only been to a couple of Nepalese restaurants but I've come to really enjoy the flavors so I was happy to see a number of items with which I was not familiar such as Samaya Baji (an interesting sampler type plate with potato pickle, fish, rice flakes, soybeans and an egg) or Khasi Ko Bhutaan (marinated goat offal). I went with the former dish and it was  really nice. Our group also opted for some of the usual suspects including pork momo (very good), goat momo (also quite good but not terribly discernible as goat),  palak chaat (which was pretty good but a bit oily), vegetable pakoras (good flavor but a bit dry...or something) and goat curry (really nice gravy and goat). Overall it was a delicious dinner and decently priced. The one thing I missed, based on my experience at other Nepalese places, was having Sel Roti on the menu.

From the warm and inviting decor to the delectable aromas (hark, might that be sandalwood incense mingling with the enticing scents of curries and tandoors?) to the soothing mountain muzak, Himalayan Heritage is a full sensory dining experience. The waitstaff is friendly, the portions are ample, and the prices are reasonable. Most importantly, the food is simply amazing - the dhindo thali, off of the Nepalese specialties menu, lived up to its name with a truly breathtaking assortment of fresh, boldly-flavored, and well-balanced curries and chutnies (I ordered my food extra spicy, and while there was significant heat, the food lost none of the subtle layers of flavor lent by the aromatic herbs and spices). Himalayan Heritage is truly a gem of a restaurant.

The curry was below average in my opinion, as it looked and tasted more like a butter chicken, not a tikka masala! In fact I still wonder now, whether they gave me the right curry... Terrible, terrible, terrible! I placed an order for take-out at 6:30pm. At 8:30pm, no delivery. Plus NO ONE is answering the phone at the restaurant. No not waste your money here!

Very poor experience indeed. We ordered tea & appetizers, but they forgot our order. We had hair in our tea. Shame.. Shame...manager/owner reflected this poor experience. Stay away from this restaurant!!!!

Became my favorite restaurant in DC immediately. We eat there almost weekly. They are fast, friendly, and most importantly the food is amazing. Have done my best to work through the entire menu, and not been let down yet. I'll get through the last few items soon, I just keep getting tempted back by my absolute favorite, Lamb Saag.  And and and, don't neglect the Nepalese specialties!
Delicious food ,better management , fast service
Great food and great people . Delicious momo

This place is what I call typical overhyped Nepalese restaurant which serves worst Nepali foods. There are some friendly folks who work there, but my objective to visit a restaurant is purely based on food. Their momo ( dumplings ) are tasteless as they don't have any juice in them. Other Nepal foods such as samay baji , chowmien ( Nepali lo mein) , and others are below average as well.  However, their Indian entrees are okay, but then again the wait is horrible. I have came to the conclusion that I would not make anymore trip to this so called Bona Fide tasteless and unauthentic Nepalese restaurant. I would recommend first timer Nepalese customers not to visit this restaurant because you would be utterly disappointed if you wanted to devour was authentic Nepalese momo and others. For rest of the folks who really doesn't care about Nepali food, this place won't disappoint you  because it would be just be like visiting any other Indian restaurant you have always been visiting.
We've done take out and dined it - one of our favorite date spots! Highly recommend the simosas or the chicken tikka misala. If you're more vegetarian inclined, the chana masala was a favorite also.
Like the variety of regional recipes. The momos and malaise kofta are really good
Authentic Indian taste. Not sure how Americans feel. Little spicy. But reminded me of Indian restaurants in india

The service here is appalling, and the food is mediocre at best. The delivery is even worse: you have a 50/50 chance of ever getting the food you order. I'd rather give up Indian food entirely than ever eat here again.

I like finding new types of cuisine and was delighted when I found this Nepalese restaurant in Adams Morgan. The food is similar to Indian but at the same time is unique and different. One this is really liked, is that the food we well prepared despite how complex the spices are. The chicken Tandoori was very good and a garlic naan. The downside is the waiting. They take a long time to get your order done. Maybe it is much faster if you are in the restaurant but it took well over an hour for our order to arrive and it ended up just stressing us out.

I went back to this restaurant after almost 2 years hoping to eat the same delicious MOMO and the magnificent Nepali thali they used to serve. However, after eating both MOMO and the Nepali thali , I don’t think I will ever visit this place again(especially for Nepali food) . It used to be a great restaurant with authentic nepali taste . Not any more . If you are looking for real nepali taste then avoid this place .

Largely Indian food on the menu but everything was very good. The chicken Khorma was my favorite.  The ambiance is nice with a beautiful and colorful Buddha mural in the back. We didn't have a reservation for 2 on a Saturday at 6pm but they took us. Great service. I also recommend the tea/vodka mixed drink. Was very good tea and not too sweet.  Nice spot!
Food is very good! Desserts are okay, not great.
Went here based on Tyler Cowen's food guide. Disappointed in the momos - they seemed bland, but the spicy eggplant and chicken masala were both very good.

Loved the food and the service. If you like vegetarian food, try the Buddha Delight - healthy and delicious. They just introduced a new cocktail menu. Manager Ramji is always on top of things, and guarantees fast en professional service. One of my favorite places in DC!
Excellent food. It was best Indian food i had in the US. Had veg Momo's , palak paneer, veg pakoras. Etc

Himalayan Heritage was a bit of a disappointment. Perhaps because I've been wanting to go for years and finally went and it didn't live up to my experience with Himalayan food in other countries (to be fair, we're talking Asia). Food is okay, though not special. It lacks brightness and spice and oomph. Meats are a bit tough and overcooked. Vegetables are lackluster. Service is nice though MIA. A request for recommendations brought the highlighting of literally every other dish on the multi-page menu. Worth a try (broaden those horizons!), but not exceptional.

The food here stands out against typical poor-quality Americanized Indian food. In particular, the chicken tikka masala had a light, fresh-tasting sauce that left me feeling satisfied. The saag was also clearly fresh-made, delicious with their hot naan. However, the meat was somewhat dry (a bummer considering how good the sauces were). Overall, good quality for a reasonable price.  I was also taken aback by the warm and attentive service.
Loved it. Great chicken saag.

For the best naan you've ever had, try their "Heritage Naan."   Whole wheat with raisins, nuts, and spices.  Amazing!  Also recommended:  Buddha Delight - something great for all you vegetarians out there :)
PRICEY!!! The food is bland and ok. Not great but good service.
